      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"total_weeks\":16,\"goal_description\":\"Return From Injury - Plantar Fasciitis Recovery & Base Rebuild\",\"phases\":[{\"phase_type\":\"Recovery\",\"weeks\":4,\"weekly_distance_start_km\":7,\"weekly_distance_end_km\":10,\"intensity_distribution\":\"100% easy / run-walk\",\"allowed_workout_types\":[\"Easy\",\"Recovery\"],\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":358,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":358,\"notes\":\"Physiotherapist-cleared easy running only. All runs capped at 20 minutes, 3 days per week. Use run-walk intervals (e.g. 4 min run / 1 min walk) at the first sign of any foot pain or stiffness. Stay at the slow end of easy pace (5:58/km). Weekly distance increases no more than 10% per week. A deload week occurs in week 4 — reduce volume by ~20% to allow tissue adaptation. No speed work of any kind. Focus: re-establish the habit of running pain-free, rebuild connective tissue tolerance, and monitor plantar fascia response carefully after each session.\",\"includes_deload\":true},{\"phase_type\":\"Base\",\"weeks\":5,\"weekly_distance_start_km\":10,\"weekly_distance_end_km\":16,\"intensity_distribution\":\"90% easy / 10% cross-train\",\"allowed_workout_types\":[\"Easy\",\"Recovery\",\"CrossTrain\"],\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":351,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":351,\"notes\":\"Gradually extend run duration beyond 20 minutes only once physiotherapist provides clearance. Until then, maintain the 20-minute cap and add a third easy run or a low-impact cross-training session (pool running, cycling, or swimming) to build aerobic volume safely. Run-walk breaks remain available at any hint of foot discomfort. Weekly distance builds at no more than 10% per week. A deload week occurs in week 8 (end of this phase) — drop volume by ~20%. Pace may ease toward the middle of the easy range (5:45/km) as fitness returns. Focus: aerobic base development, tendon and fascial loading tolerance, and gradual duration extension.\",\"includes_deload\":true},{\"phase_type\":\"Build\",\"weeks\":4,\"weekly_distance_start_km\":16,\"weekly_distance_end_km\":22,\"intensity_distribution\":\"80% easy / 20% moderate (tempo only if cleared)\",\"allowed_workout_types\":[\"Easy\",\"LongRun\",\"Tempo\",\"CrossTrain\"],\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":344,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":269,\"notes\":\"Tempo and harder efforts are introduced ONLY after explicit physiotherapist clearance for speed work. If not yet cleared, keep all runs easy and continue cross-training for the quality component. The long run on Saturday begins to extend — target 45-60 minutes easy by the end of this phase. Weekly distance increases no more than 10% per week. A deload week occurs in week 12 — reduce volume by ~20%. Pace may progress toward 5:24/km on easy days. Threshold pace target is 4:29/km but only use this if fully cleared and pain-free for at least 4 consecutive weeks. Focus: re-introduction of moderate intensity, long run extension, and continued plantar fascia monitoring.\",\"includes_deload\":true},{\"phase_type\":\"Peak\",\"weeks\":2,\"weekly_distance_start_km\":22,\"weekly_distance_end_km\":25,\"intensity_distribution\":\"80/20 easy/hard\",\"allowed_workout_types\":[\"Easy\",\"LongRun\",\"Tempo\",\"Interval\",\"CrossTrain\"],\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":324,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":252,\"notes\":\"Peak training block — only reached if James has been pain-free and fully cleared by his physiotherapist. Weekly volume reaches a modest peak of ~25 km across 3 days, which is appropriate given the 3-day-per-week constraint and injury history. Long run on Saturday targets 60-70 minutes. One quality session per week (tempo or controlled intervals at threshold pace 4:29/km or interval pace 4:12/km). No deload in this short block — the subsequent taper serves that purpose. Focus: consolidate fitness gains, confirm readiness to return to normal training, and celebrate the comeback.\",\"includes_deload\":false},{\"phase_type\":\"Taper\",\"weeks\":1,\"weekly_distance_start_km\":15,\"weekly_distance_end_km\":15,\"intensity_distribution\":\"90% easy / 10% strides\",\"allowed_workout_types\":[\"Easy\",\"Recovery\"],\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":344,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":324,\"notes\":\"Final week is a light taper and transition week. Volume drops ~40% from peak. All runs are easy. This week marks the successful completion of the return-from-injury plan and sets James up to transition into a standard base-building or race-prep plan. Reflect on progress, check in with physiotherapist for a final clearance assessment, and plan the next training block. Focus: freshness, confidence, and readiness for the next chapter.\",\"includes_deload\":false}],\"rationale\":\"James is returning from active plantar fasciitis with physiotherapist clearance for easy running only, capped at 20 minutes per session, 3 days per week. His pre-injury VDOT of 46.5 (44:00 10K) indicates solid intermediate fitness, but current fitness is likely meaningfully lower after the injury layoff. The plan is built around four non-negotiable principles: (1) tissue tolerance before fitness — the plantar fascia and surrounding structures must adapt before volume or intensity increases; (2) strict 10% weekly volume progression with deload every 3-4 weeks to prevent re-injury; (3) no speed work until physiotherapist clearance is confirmed, with cross-training used to maintain aerobic stimulus safely; and (4) run-walk protocols as a standing tool whenever foot pain or stiffness appears. The 16-week structure moves through Recovery → Base → Build → Peak → Taper, with each phase gated by pain-free progress. Paces are derived from James's VDOT 46.5 using Daniels' Running Formula: easy runs stay at 5:58–5:24/km, threshold at 4:29/km, and intervals at 4:12/km — but faster paces are only introduced in later phases and only with full clearance. The Saturday long run anchor respects James's stated preference and provides the primary aerobic stimulus each week.\",\"warnings\":\"IMPORTANT: James has active plantar fasciitis. This plan is designed for someone cleared by a physiotherapist for easy running only. (1) If foot pain increases, worsens, or does not resolve within the first 5 minutes of a run, STOP the run immediately and consult your physiotherapist before running again. (2) No speed work, tempo, or interval sessions until your physiotherapist explicitly clears you — this plan includes those sessions in later phases as conditional options only. (3) Run-walk breaks are not optional if you feel foot pain — use them without hesitation. (4) Morning stiffness in the heel or arch that lasts more than 10-15 minutes is a warning sign; flag this with your physiotherapist. (5) This plan does not constitute medical advice. Your physiotherapist's guidance takes absolute precedence over any element of this plan. (6) Do not progress to the next phase if you are not pain-free — repeat the current phase instead.\"}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
